Leica S Typ 006 + Leica 35-90mm Vario Elmar-S. At the Ferry Building, San Francisco, California.

Still getting used to DoF with this S lens (24-70mm equivalent focal length in 35mm terms). With a 35mm camera with a full-size sensor (e.g., Nikon D810, D800E), at a focal length of 24mm, I think I would get all of these in good focus. With the larger sensor in the S, the DoF is more shallow, and it takes a higher f-stop to get the same DoF as a 35mm camera would get.

Here, I focused on the middle row of price tags, which is in sharp focus. The back row of price tags are also in very good focus, but the nearest price tags obviously are a bit out of the DoF range.

Six dollars for a pound of tomatoes?! With sales tax, it is even higher: $6.50. That is absurd, even for an "heirloom". No, I did not buy any!

photo.title: Inside the Ferry Building (L1002853)

description._content:
Leica S Typ 006 + Leica 30-90mm Vario Elmar-S. After only a handful of test shots, it becomes quite evident that the 30-90 zoom can take on any prime lens at a similar focal length. Very impressive design by Leica.

This is the inside of the San Francisco Ferry Building. Once it used to be the main ticketing office and ferry station for going past the city. But after the Golden Gate bridge, and later, the even bigger San Francisco-Oakland Bay bridge were built, the ferry building and adjacent structures were converted into stores and restaurants for the most part.

This place is always teeming with people. It is so crowded that it's often hard to walk in a straight line. The last time I was here, I took the shot below with my Sony A7R and Zeiss Otus 55/1.4. In that, I tried to capture the whole scene, to get a feel for the place. This time, I decided to aim above the heads of the crowds and just concentrate on the ceiling and side walls.

Ideally, a picture like this should be taken on a tripod, so the camera can be perfectly aligned to be orthogonal to the scene. But no time for all of that, so it was taken hand held. So a slight cropping was necessary to make the image more symmetrical. Apart from that, no post-processing.

The full resolution (after the crop) is uploaded, in case anyone wants to take a closer look.

The structure was demolished in 1991, after being damaged by the Loma Prieta quake in 1989. Today, this view has been completely transformed, and includes the F Line heritage streetcar line, and the Ferry Plaza.. Original slide - photographer unknown See where this photo was taken

photo.title: Sk8ers

description._content:
Captured in front of San Francisco's Ferry Building in 2013 (I marked it as August 9, 2013 in EXIF).  I had just bought this Olympus OM-1n in flea market in very good condition, so I took it for a spin.  This was a single shot effort.  I felt very good about it, so I didn't take my usual bracket shots for safety.  For that reason, I consider this as my masterpiece.  LOL  But the lack of shutter lag of OM-1n is remarkable (that camera was sold, because I prefer my OM-4T's "modern" convenience, but it's still a fine specimen).

I was sick and tired of jotting down exposure notes during that time, so no exposure info, but I believe this to be 1/125" or 1/60" (just enough to blur this super fast motion and still remain sharp while handheld).  I usually shot at an ISO that's one stop under, so I believe this was shot at ISO 50.  Don't know the aperture, but I am guessing it's f/8.  The lens is most likely be 50mm f/1.8 that came with it, and the filter (if used) would be orange, but I doubt it, because I was testing the camera.

Olympus OM-1n
Kodak Delta 100 (35mm B&W film)
